Project Foundations for Data Science: FoodHub Data Analysis

Marks: 60

Context

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

# First: filter restaurants with more than 50 ratings

ratings_given = df[df['rating'] != 'Not given'].copy()
ratings_given['rating'] = ratings_given['rating'].astype(int)
restaurant_rating_counts = ratings_given['restaurant_name'].value_counts()
restaurants_50_ratings = restaurant_rating_counts[restaurant_rating_counts > 50]

# Second: filter by rating > 4

average_rating = ratings_given.groupby('restaurant_name')['rating'].mean()
eligible_restaurants = average_rating[average_rating > 4].index.intersection(restaurants_50_ratings.index)

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders. [3 marks]

In[35]:
revenue = 0

for index, order in df.iterrows(): # iterate over the indexes and rows of the dataframe
    if order['cost_of_the_order'] > 20: # check if the cost of the order is greater than 20
        revenue += order['cost_of_the_order'] * 0.25
    elif order['cost_of_the_order'] > 5: # check if the cost of the order is greater than 5 and not greater than 20, because those were filtered in the previous condition.
        revenue += order['cost_of_the_order'] * 0.15

revenue

The revenue across all orders is 6166.30 USD

Conclusion and Recommendations

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations.) [6 marks]

Conclusions:

  • A few restaurants, such as Shake Shack, The Meatball Shop, and Blue Ribbon Sushi, have a significantly higher number of orders compared to others.
  • With cuisine types happend something similar, a few cuisine types have significant more orders than others, being american foor the most popular. It is completly normal, because the data come from the US.
  • The rest popular cuisine types are the most common on other countries too like chinese, japanese and italian and this is also easily explained because of the high number of emigrants leaving these countries.
  • The costs of the orders are clearly right-skewed, indicating that while most orders are relatively not expensive, there are a few order significantly more expensive. This could be related with better quallity products or more fancy food.
  • Weekday vs Weekend: Difference is evident how costumers preffers to order food on weekends than on weekdays. It id related to people bringing food the weekdays to school/job or schools/employer having daily meals for students/employees, as much as people going directly to the restaurant to get his daily meal instead of ordering food.
  • On average the ratings are good, meaning that costumers likes the service provided and food is usually good, but still more than the half of costumers preffers to not give a rating to the order (it could be because of the time it takes or just they don't want to share this information).
  • The food preparation time has a 20-35 min window with a uniform distribution (same probablity for each time). It's pretty consistent, not depending much on the cuisine type or restaurant, but there are some cuisine types that have a lower average preparation time than the average of the rest, but nothing too significant.
  • Delivery time is also right-skewed, it could be because some orders are made far away from the restaurant taking a bit longer, but most of the orders are delivered in a reasonable time. Delivery time is signifitantly higher on weeks because of trafic and people moving more on weekdays than weekends.
  • Delivery time has a significant impact on the ratings. High delivery times means lower ratings normally.
  • Cost of the order has an impact on the ratings too, with higher costs normally giving as result higher ratings to the respective order. As said before, it could be related with better products used for the preparation of the orders and also more fancy restaurants that usually get higher ratings.

After all we can see how a lot of these variable can affect ratings that is one of the most importants parameters that costumers use to chose the restaurant. Cost is not that significant, because the mean order cost is not signifitantly different between different restaurants, neither cuisine types.

Recommendations:

  • Start by implementing discount coupon strategies for restaurants with a high number of orders. Prioritize those that are in greater demand and highly rated. Offering discounts for the most popular restaurants can encourage even more orders, improving customer satisfaction and loyalty (the discount for most popular and well evaluated restaurants is a good iniciative).
  • At the same time offering discount for recently incorporated restaurants is good to make them more visible and get ratings from costumers, giving them the chance to sell more and increase the revenue.
  • Introduce themed discount days for popular types of cuisine, such as "Italian Day," "Chinese Day," or "Japanese Day." These special offers can drive customer interest and increase orders for specific cuisines on selected days.
  • Use some offer for weekdays (last point recomandation can be used for this purpose) to promote costumers to order food also on weekdays to increase the sales. This has to be connected with the next point, becuase weekday delivery time is usally higher.
  • Try to speed up with better path fiding algorithms the delivery times, because higher delivery times are affecting negativly the rating of the orders. As preparation time is equal across the timeline there is not much to do about it to shorten these times.
  • Use the information from the total order time (preparation time + delivery time) as a measure of how long it takes to recieve the food. Since it has an normal distribution its mean is good to estimate the time the order is gonna take to arrive giving the costumers and yourself a better planification.
  • Do not change much the order system, neither the restaurants, because the ratings are good.
  • Try to have an easier and/or faster rating system to get more feedback from the costumers.
